04221nam a22006375i 9780226515809DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017025972  a9780226515809  a(DE-B1597)523923  a(OCoLC)1022634693  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJC71.P6bF735 2018 4aJC71.P6bF735 2019 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a321.07223  aFH 28715qDE-24/20sred2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/31083:1 aFrank, Jill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoetic Justice :bRereading Plato's "Republic" /cJill Frank. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue: Learning to Read -- t1. Reading Plato -- t2. Poetry: The Measure of Truth -- t3. A Life without Poetry -- t4. The Power of Persuasion -- t5. Erōs: The Work of Desire -- t6. Dialectics: Making Sense of Logos -- tWork Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen Plato set his dialogs, written texts were disseminated primarily by performance and recitation. He wrote them, however, when literacy was expanding. Jill Frank argues that there are unique insights to be gained from appreciating Plato’s dialogs as written texts to be read and reread. At the center of these insights are two distinct ways of learning to read in the dialogs. One approach that appears in the Statesman, Sophist, and Protagoras, treats learning to read as a top-down affair, in which authoritative teachers lead students to true beliefs. Another, recommended by Socrates, encourages trial and error and the formation of beliefs based on students’ own fallible experiences. In all of these dialogs, learning to read is likened to coming to know or understand something. Given Plato’s repeated presentation of the analogy between reading and coming to know, what can these two approaches tell us about his dialogs’ representations of philosophy and politics? With Poetic Justice, Jill Frank overturns the conventional view that the Republic endorses a hierarchical ascent to knowledge and the authoritarian politics associated with that philosophy. When learning to read is understood as the passive absorption of a teacher’s beliefs, this reflects the account of Platonic philosophy as authoritative knowledge wielded by philosopher kings who ruled the ideal city. When we learn to read by way of the method Socrates introduces in the Republic, Frank argues, we are offered an education in ethical and political self-governance, one that prompts citizens to challenge all claims to authority, including those of philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 0aReadingxPhilosophy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aPlato.  aRepublic.  aauthority.  adesire.  apersuasion.  aphilosophy.  apoetry.  apolitics.  aself-governance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022651563240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226515809423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226515809/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles